#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:204
msgid "Support for complex numbers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:206
msgid ""
"C99-like complex functions have been added. Those can be used if you wish to "
"implement portable C extensions. Since NumPy 2.0 we use C99 complex types as "
"the underlying type:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:210
msgid ""
"typedef double _Complex npy_cdouble;\n"
"typedef float _Complex npy_cfloat;\n"
"typedef long double _Complex npy_clongdouble;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:216
msgid ""
"MSVC does not support the ``_Complex`` type itself, but has added support "
"for the C99 ``complex.h`` header by providing its own implementation. Thus, "
"under MSVC, the equivalent MSVC types will be used:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:220
msgid ""
"typedef _Dcomplex npy_cdouble;\n"
"typedef _Fcomplex npy_cfloat;\n"
"typedef _Lcomplex npy_clongdouble;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:226
msgid ""
"Because MSVC still does not support C99 syntax for initializing a complex "
"number, you need to restrict to C90-compatible syntax, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:229
msgid ""
"/* a = 1 + 2i \\*/\n"
"npy_complex a = npy_cpack(1, 2);\n"
"npy_complex b;\n"
"\n"
"b = npy_log(a);"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:237
msgid ""
"A few utilities have also been added in ``numpy/npy_math.h``, in order to "
"retrieve or set the real or the imaginary part of a complex number:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:241
msgid ""
"npy_cdouble c;\n"
"npy_csetreal(&c, 1.0);\n"
"npy_csetimag(&c, 0.0);\n"
"printf(\"%d + %di\\n\", npy_creal(c), npy_cimag(c));"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:250
msgid ""
"The underlying C types for all of numpy's complex types have been changed to "
"use C99 complex types. Up until now the following was being used to "
"represent complex types:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:254
msgid ""
"typedef struct { double real, imag; } npy_cdouble;\n"
"typedef struct { float real, imag; } npy_cfloat;\n"
"typedef struct {npy_longdouble real, imag;} npy_clongdouble;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:260
msgid ""
"Using the ``struct`` representation ensured that complex numbers could be "
"used on all platforms, even the ones without support for built-in complex "
"types. It also meant that a static library had to be shipped together with "
"NumPy to provide a C99 compatibility layer for downstream packages to use. "
"In recent years however, support for native complex types has been improved "
"immensely, with MSVC adding built-in support for the ``complex.h`` header in "
"2019."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:267
msgid ""
"To ease cross-version compatibility, macros that use the new set APIs have "
"been added."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:270
msgid ""
"#define NPY_CSETREAL(z, r) npy_csetreal(z, r)\n"
"#define NPY_CSETIMAG(z, i) npy_csetimag(z, i)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:275
msgid ""
"A compatibility layer is also provided in ``numpy/npy_2_complexcompat.h``. "
"It checks whether the macros exist, and falls back to the 1.x syntax in case "
"they don't."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:279
msgid ""
"#include <numpy/npy_math.h>\n"
"\n"
"#ifndef NPY_CSETREALF\n"
"#define NPY_CSETREALF(c, r) (c)->real = (r)\n"
"#endif\n"
"#ifndef NPY_CSETIMAGF\n"
"#define NPY_CSETIMAGF(c, i) (c)->imag = (i)\n"
"#endif"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:290
msgid ""
"We suggest all downstream packages that need this functionality to copy-"
"paste the compatibility layer code into their own sources and use that, so "
"that they can continue to support both NumPy 1.x and 2.x without issues. "
"Note also that the ``complex.h`` header is included in ``numpy/npy_common."
"h``, which makes ``complex`` a reserved keyword."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:299
msgid "Linking against the core math library in an extension"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:301
msgid ""
"To use the core math library that NumPy ships as a static library in your "
"own Python extension, you need to add the ``npymath`` compile and link "
"options to your extension. The exact steps to take will depend on the build "
"system you are using. The generic steps to take are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:306
msgid ""
"Add the numpy include directory (= the value of ``np.get_include()``) to "
"your include directories,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:308
msgid ""
"The ``npymath`` static library resides in the ``lib`` directory right next "
"to numpy's include directory (i.e., ``pathlib.Path(np.get_include()) / "
"'..' / 'lib'``). Add that to your library search directories,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:311
msgid "Link with ``libnpymath`` and ``libm``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:315
msgid ""
"Keep in mind that when you are cross compiling, you must use the ``numpy`` "
"for the platform you are building for, not the native one for the build "
"machine. Otherwise you pick up a static library built for the wrong "
"architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:320
msgid ""
"When you build with ``numpy.distutils`` (deprecated), then use this in your "
"``setup.py``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:331
msgid ""
"In other words, the usage of ``info`` is exactly the same as when using "
"``blas_info`` and co."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:334
msgid "When you are building with `Meson <https://mesonbuild.com>`__, use::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:336
msgid ""
"# Note that this will get easier in the future, when Meson has\n"
"# support for numpy built in; most of this can then be replaced\n"
"# by `dependency('numpy')`.\n"
"incdir_numpy = run_command(py3,\n"
"  [\n"
"    '-c',\n"
"    'import os; os.chdir(\"..\"); import numpy; print(numpy.get_include())'\n"
"  ],\n"
"  check: true\n"
").stdout().strip()\n"
"\n"
"inc_np = include_directories(incdir_numpy)\n"
"\n"
"cc = meson.get_compiler('c')\n"
"npymath_path = incdir_numpy / '..' / 'lib'\n"
"npymath_lib = cc.find_library('npymath', dirs: npymath_path)\n"
"\n"
"py3.extension_module('module_name',\n"
"  ...\n"
"  include_directories: inc_np,\n"
"  dependencies: [npymath_lib],"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:359
msgid "Half-precision functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:361
msgid ""
"The header file ``<numpy/halffloat.h>`` provides functions to work with IEEE "
"754-2008 16-bit floating point values. While this format is not typically "
"used for numerical computations, it is useful for storing values which "
"require floating point but do not need much precision. It can also be used "
"as an educational tool to understand the nature of floating point round-off "
"error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:368
msgid ""
"Like for other types, NumPy includes a typedef npy_half for the 16 bit "
"float.  Unlike for most of the other types, you cannot use this as a normal "
"type in C, since it is a typedef for npy_uint16.  For example, 1.0 looks "
"like 0x3c00 to C, and if you do an equality comparison between the different "
"signed zeros, you will get -0.0 != 0.0 (0x8000 != 0x0000), which is "
"incorrect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:375
msgid ""
"For these reasons, NumPy provides an API to work with npy_half values "
"accessible by including ``<numpy/halffloat.h>`` and linking to ``npymath``. "
"For functions that are not provided directly, such as the arithmetic "
"operations, the preferred method is to convert to float or double and back "
"again, as in the following example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/coremath.rst:381
msgid ""
"npy_half sum(int n, npy_half *array) {\n"
"    float ret = 0;\n"
"    while(n--) {\n"
"        ret += npy_half_to_float(*array++);\n"
"    }\n"
"    return npy_float_to_half(ret);\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

